of his life Hooper came to prominence for his exceptional career and place in the history of jazz, inspiring an autobiography that was never published. Statesman of the Piano makes this document widely available for the first time and includes photographs, concert programs, lyrics, and other documents to reconstruct his life and times. Historians, archivists, musicians, and cultural critics provide annotations and commentary, examining some of the themes that emerge from Hooper’s writing and music.Statesman of the Piano sparks new conversations about Hooper’s legacy while shedding light on the cross-border travels and wartime experiences of Black musicians, the politics of archiving and curating, and the connections between race and music in the twentieth century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aJazz musicianszCanadavBiography. 0aMusicians, BlackzCanadavBiography. 0aPianistszCanadavBiography. 7aMUSIC / History & Criticism.2bisacsh  aAfrican diaspora.  aBlack Canadian.  aBuxton.  aDetroit.  aHarlem Renaissance.  aMontreal.  aMusicians.  aNew York.  aQuebec.  aSound.  aToronto.  aWorld War II.  aarchives.  aautobiography.  ablues.  aborder.  aclassical.  afolk songs.  ajazz.  alife story.  amemory.  amigration.  arace records.  aragtim.1 aDesai, Arshad Suliman, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFillion, Eric, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFillion, Eric, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHooper, Lou, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMills, Sean, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMills, Sean, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aNigam, Sunita, econtributor.4ctb4https:/